Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden changes in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because, coming out of the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many aspects, particularly from the perspective of sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the cause of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove.
Next, predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed, and when no credit is available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly non-linear events that occur without warning signs.
Periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible.
If this pattern were to repeat, it could undermine confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could lead to excessive regulations, state intervention, and a withdrawal from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is turning into a crisis of sovereign debt in advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can translate into a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bailout spending.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of "fiscal packages" in advanced economies include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
Unidentified imbalances and systemic risks mean that fiscal policies that seem prudent are not actually prudent.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But its revenues and expenditures were largely determined by a real estate bubble linked to very high levels of debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is probably a typical example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructurings or through inflation.
If systemic risks can cause this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, it is necessary for "sovereign" states to be alert to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and taking corrective measures quickly.
New detailed legislative frameworks, emphasizing capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection and resolution mechanisms, are about to be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will do nothing to resolve the issue of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and signaling instability.
In addition and as a complement to new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some politicians and top analysts consider such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, to be futile.
The incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex, constantly evolving global financial system mean, according to them, that risk detection is either impossible or so prone to error that this effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are nearly impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we must then accept that we will periodically find ourselves in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than the one we considered necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under conditions of uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists of rejecting a true proposition, and the other is accepting a false proposition.
Let us call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be posed in these terms: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the most probable high cost?
Opponents of prudent surveillance of systemic risks have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable early warning sign of a potentially increasing instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantaneously.
But this position seems fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note of them.
We must, however, admit that these warnings may not have been sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the breaking point.
They were undeniably signs.
The second position is that there are indeed early warning signs, but they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF has a higher probable cost than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or the remedy is worse than the illness.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with the AQF error.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so that the aggregate negative effect of a reaction to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced.
There may be a deeper trend towards openness.
Whether in business or investments, decisions are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty and errors are frequent.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems to be that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply rooted belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless one has good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at best questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try the experiment, and assign for this purpose responsibilities to a new institution, or an existing institution, that has access to relevant information, that possesses analytical skills at both the financial and macroeconomic levels, and that is relatively free from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the ability of the financial system to self-regulate.
